##Japanese cruise expert apologizes for 'chaos' in video

The papernews

The function introduction, has the connotation the current politics new media

Reporter of the paper, Liu Dong, intern, Liu Yukun

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Kentaro Iwata

Japanese infectious disease expert Kentaro Iwata deleted the video he posted on social media early Monday after it received more than a million hits in 24 hours.

"I decided that there was no need for further discussion, so I deleted the video. I apologize to those affected and thank you, " Iwata said on social media.

On the evening of the 18th, Iwada revealed through social media what he had seen on the diamond princess that day. In the video released, he sharply criticized the lax management of the ship's epidemic prevention, the bureaucracy in charge of everything and the lack of experts, resulting in the virus "everywhere, " and admitted that as a senior epidemic prevention expert, he was also "very afraid" of being infected. After the video was released, it attracted a lot of attention in Japan. The Japanese government, opposition parties and the public have expressed different views.

"The government has not released any information about the inside of the cruise ship for two weeks, making it impossible to know what happened on the cruise ship, " Iwata told the paper in an interview on the evening of 19 www.thepaper.cn  . The next morning, he deleted his video, saying he could not be reached for further comment.

On the 19th, the Japanese government has started the procedure of disembarking tourists from cruise ships. The first 500 passengers disembarked that same day. On the same day, 79 new cases of coronavirus infection were added to the cruise, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 621. Two passengers of the "Diamond Princess" cruise ship have died after being diagnosed with a new case of pneumonia, a Japanese government source said Sunday. On the same day, more passengers will disembark and embark on the journey home.

Official: IWADA was removed from the ship for incompetence

Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare official Yihao Gao posted a long message on social media on Thursday night, acknowledging that he was the official who initially helped Dr. Iwada board the ship and responding to a number of questions raised by Iwada in the video.

"His statement may be too strong for someone who doesn't know Iwada. The content could have a negative impact on passengers and staff working on the ground. So while admitting the truth, as the person involved in the video, allow me to clarify what has been misunderstood and omitted,"he said.

IWADA's "arduous" journey aboard the ship ended with him being a member of Japan's Disaster Medical Response Team (DMAT) rather than an infectious disease specialist. The reason, he explained, was that passengers were being disembarked at the scene, in which case the fear that Mr. Iwada would be "kept at arm's length" if experts suddenly instructed him to do so would also affect the continuation of the disembarkation.

In fact, Iwada was only on board for two hours before he was kicked off the ship, Gao said. The main area he saw was the area around the hall. "I think cruises are a special space and not something you can look around and give an opinion about, " he said.

In the video, Iwata described the scene as "chaotic" and said there was no distinction between the uninfected "Green Zone" (safe zone) and the "red zone" (danger zone) that could be contaminated by the virus. "people with a fever come out of their rooms and walk to the infirmary, " he said. "people walk around in personal protective equipment, eat in the same place and even wear protective gloves when they eat. "

In response, Takayama said, "As an infectious disease doctor, [ Iwada described the scene ] as chaos, which I can understand. But the way he expresses it can lead to the misconception that there are no zones at all. But in fact, the zoning was strictly enforced. Although it may not be perfect."And for walking people, takayama thinks it's not the patient, but some of the passengers. "Even for passengers, I think it's rare, " he said.

"indeed, more sophisticated infection control would be implemented in hospitals in developed countries or in medical centres established in developing countries or by international organizations. But all of a sudden, on a ship with about 3,700 people and a lot of old people... the task of quarantine is extremely complicated,"he explained.

IWADA also said in the video, "In more than 20 years of epidemic prevention work, I have never felt so much risk of infection, not even when I was fighting Zaire ebolavirus in Africa and SARS [ Atypical pneumonia ] in Beijing. "

In response, Gao Shan said, "It's a matter of Iwada's sensitivity, so I won't deny it. You can't not be afraid of an epidemic in a confined space like a ship. But I hope you can understand that some people are continuing to work on it. "

"There are a lot of challenges, but we have made a little bit of progress and certainly there is room for improvement. At least we can not allow passengers to go ashore until all the operations have been completed, " he said.

Complaints that Iwada said his advice was not taken, that some officials were not happy and that he was eventually removed from the ship. The mountain responded, "In addition to the DMAT, there are the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare, the self-defence forces and, most importantly, the captain-led side of the ship, so there is a lot of decision-making going on. [ Mr. Iwada ] by not understanding the complexities, you're breaking our agreement. At least he would have called me and communicated, but he gave me direct advice on infection control from all sides."

"He was forced off the ship because he was not up to the job. Of course, as an infectious disease doctor, Mr. Iwada's advice is largely sound. But if we focus on giving the right advice, there's a chance the organization won't work. Especially in crisis management, trust is more important than anything else."

The mountain also further indicated that, "criticism is OK, but I want to avoid creating panic if it doesn't solve the problem... infectious disease doctors need to be able to act as consultants. It's also an ability to make people want to listen. When people don't listen to me, I don't think it's their fault. It was the way I explained it."

The Japanese government and the experts disagree

The Japanese government also responded to Iwada's video on the 19th.

Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshihide Suga responded at a news conference that day that the Japanese government had taken all measures to prevent the epidemic from spreading, the Daily News reported, he said he would be open to all kinds of criticism from the community.

Yoshihide Suga told a news conference that "there is no yes or no answer" to criticism that "it is difficult to distinguish between safe areas and dangerous areas" . Regarding measures to prevent infection, he said that he had made sure that every crew member wore a mask, washed his hands and disinfected himself with alcohol. If the crew is confirmed to be infected, the crew in the same room will also have to be quarantined to prevent further outbreaks.

The Asahi Shimbun quoted a Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare official as saying that the allegation in Iwata's video that "there are no infectious disease experts on board and that it is entirely up to the layman to prevent the spread of the disease" was untrue, there were doctors and nurses on board WHO KNEW A lot about infectious diseases, and the ship's epidemic prevention work was guided by the Infectious Diseases Society. But Sakurai, a professor at Iwate Medical University and a member of the Japanese environmental infection society who boarded the ship, admitted in an interview Thursday that no expert had spent much time on the ship.

Japan's National Institute of Infectious Diseases for the first time released the results of an analysis of a mass infection of COVID-19 pneumonia on the "Diamond Princess" cruise ship, many of the passengers were infected before quarantine measures were taken, the agency said. The infection could have spread through the events on the ship. At the same time, the report noted an increase in infections among crew members after 10 days, which the study attributed to incomplete isolation as some crew members continued to perform the necessary work to keep the ship running.

Professor Sakurai further noted that "there are two peaks of infection on board the ship... It is assumed that it was initially transmitted between passengers attending parties and buffets, and then spread through the services provided by the crew. ".

However, experts also said that because of the limited number of cases reported and the fact that some people are currently asymptomatic but may become ill in the future, "it is not possible to conclude that the number of infections decreased after the tourists were isolated in the room. ".
